# Domain guard clauses

Use **Ardalis GuardClauses** (`Guard.Against.*`) for input and precondition validation in domain factories, constructors, and methods.

Do **not** use manual `if` blocks that throw `InvalidOperationException` for these cases.

## Use Guard for

| Check | Guard |
|-------|-------|
| Null reference | `Guard.Against.Null(value)` |
| Null/empty collection | `Guard.Against.NullOrEmpty(items)` |
| Null/whitespace string | `Guard.Against.NullOrWhiteSpace(value)` |
| Negative decimal | `Guard.Against.Negative(amount)` |
| Negative or zero | `Guard.Against.NegativeOrZero(amount)` |
| Out of range length | `Guard.Against.OutOfRange(length, paramName, min, max)` |

`NullOrEmpty` covers null collections — do not also call `Null` on the same value.

## Keep InvalidOperationException for

Business rules and **state/lifecycle** violations only (wrong status, illegal transition), e.g. `Order.Accept()` when not Pending.

## Tests

Domain tests for guard failures should expect `ArgumentException`, not `InvalidOperationException` with custom messages.

## Example

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — manual precondition checks
if (subtotal < 0m)
    throw new InvalidOperationException("Subtotal cannot be negative.");
if (items.Count <= 0)
    throw new InvalidOperationException("Invoice items must have one or more item.");

// ✅ GOOD
Guard.Against.Negative(subtotal);
Guard.Against.Negative(totalPrice);
Guard.Against.NullOrEmpty(items);
```

Reference: `Invoice.Create`, `Batch`, `Allocation`, `ImmediateReturn`, `OrderPayment`.
